          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Data Leakage vs Data Exfiltration"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Data exfiltration is an attacker deliberately extracting information from a system. Data leakage is the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "accidental",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " exposure of information \u2014 through log files, error messages, shared state, or overly broad context passed to sub-agents. Leakage is often more prevalent than exfiltration because it requires no attacker: it happens as a side effect of normal operation."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In agentic systems, leakage is amplified by three factors: the agent's context window is large and multi-user deployments share infrastructure, the agent's outputs are often stored (for debugging, evaluation, and fine-tuning), and the agent can spawn sub-agents that receive a copy of the conversation context."
          }
        ]
      },
